    <section class="band" id="start-here">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Local</span>
          <h2>Start here</h2>
        </div>
        <dl class="faq">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does AtlasArc run locally?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. AtlasArc runs inside IntelliJ IDEA and analyzes your project on your machine. It is a local IDE tool, not a hosted scanner. See the <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Is my source code uploaded anywhere?</dt>
            <dd>No. The plugin does not transmit source code, metrics, project data, or personal information to AtlasArc or any third party. It reads the project locally and renders the analysis inside the IDE. See the <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Which IntelliJ IDEA versions are supported?</dt>
            <dd>AtlasArc runs on IntelliJ IDEA 2023.3 or later. The <a href="/docs/getting-started">getting started guide</a> covers install and first analysis.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does it work with Community and Ultimate?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. AtlasArc works with IntelliJ IDEA Community and Ultimate. You do not need Ultimate just to run AtlasArc.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="project-compatibility">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Project</span>
          <h2>Project compatibility</h2>
        </div>
        <dl class="faq">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does AtlasArc support Java and Kotlin?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. AtlasArc analyzes Java and Kotlin projects through compiled JVM bytecode. The public language pages explain what the JVM analyzer reads for <a href="/languages/java">Java</a> and <a href="/languages/kotlin">Kotlin</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>What Java and Kotlin constructs are recognized?</dt>
            <dd>The accurate claim is bytecode-visible JVM dependencies: class structure, type signatures, inheritance, bytecode-retained annotations, calls, field access, casts, class literals, lambdas, Kotlin declarations that compile to JVM output, and similar relationships. It is not a promise to detect every source-only relationship.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does it work with Gradle and Maven?</dt>
            <dd>Yes, as long as IntelliJ imports the project and the project builds. AtlasArc does not require a Gradle or Maven plugin for analysis. See <a href="/docs/getting-started">Getting started</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Do I need to change my build files?</dt>
            <dd>No. AtlasArc does not edit application build files for analysis or governance. It writes only its committed governance document after you review the diff. To enforce decisions in CI, build your project normally and add a pipeline step that runs the <a href="/docs/govern-cycle-exceptions#ci">AtlasArc evaluator</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Why should I build before analysis?</dt>
            <dd>AtlasArc reads compiled class files for Java and Kotlin. A fresh build gives the most accurate graph; stale class files can show packages that have moved or miss code that was just added.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does it work with multi-module projects?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. AtlasArc can analyze the whole project or individual IntelliJ modules. Multi-module cycle noise is handled explicitly, including cross-module cycles that are hidden by default unless you ask to inspect them. See <a href="/docs/handling-large-projects">handling large projects</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Can it handle large projects?</dt>
            <dd>AtlasArc's large-project strategy is reduction: scope the model, roll up depth, switch to the right lens, pin a subject, and inspect the exact cycle, boundary, hotspot, or subsystem you care about. See <a href="/docs/handling-large-projects">handling large projects</a>.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band" id="typescript">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">TS</span>
          <h2>TypeScript</h2>
        </div>
        <dl class="faq">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does AtlasArc support TypeScript?</dt>
            <dd>Yes, through generated dependency-cruiser JSON artifacts. AtlasArc turns those artifacts into a local architecture model for TypeScript source folders and files. Start with <a href="/languages/typescript">TypeScript support</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>What files do I need to generate?</dt>
            <dd><code>.atlasarc/depgraph.json</code> is required. <code>.atlasarc/eslint.sarif</code> is optional for complexity enrichment. LCOV coverage can be loaded manually after the TypeScript graph is available. See <a href="/languages/typescript">TypeScript support</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does AtlasArc run Node, npm, or dependency-cruiser for me?</dt>
            <dd>No. Your repository generates the artifacts with its own package manager, workspace configuration, path aliases, and CI environment. AtlasArc reads the resulting files. See <a href="/languages/typescript">TypeScript support</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Are Java/Kotlin and TypeScript shown in one combined graph?</dt>
            <dd>No. JVM and TypeScript sources are selected and analyzed separately. Cross-language API contracts are future work, not part of the current model.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Are all JVM metrics available for TypeScript?</dt>
            <dd>No. TypeScript gets source-folder/file dependency exploration and available artifact-backed metrics, but JVM-specific metrics such as abstractness, distance from the main sequence, relative visibility, ARV, and GRV are unavailable.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="architecture-workflow">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Workflow</span>
          <h2>Architecture workflow</h2>
        </div>
        <dl class="faq">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>How is AtlasArc different from IntelliJ's built-in dependency tools?</dt>
            <dd>IntelliJ IDEA already has useful dependency tools. AtlasArc is for the next step: turning dependency inspection into architecture exploration, cycle triage, hotspot prioritization, governance, and reporting. See the <a href="/compare#intellij-built-in-dependency-tools">IntelliJ comparison</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>How is AtlasArc different from Sonar?</dt>
            <dd>Sonar is a broader static-analysis and governance platform. AtlasArc is the local IntelliJ architecture workbench for exploring structure, diagnosing dependencies, and preparing architecture evidence. See the <a href="/compare#codemr-sonar">Sonar comparison</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>What are Safe Havens?</dt>
            <dd>Safe Havens are workspace-local suppressions for narrowing an investigation. They keep noise out of the current review without creating a committed team decision. See <a href="/docs/govern-cycle-exceptions#safe-havens">Govern cycle exceptions</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>What are repository governance records?</dt>
            <dd>They are committed AtlasArc decisions that mark a directed dependency as intentional or tracked debt. A required reason and optional ticket travel in <code>.atlasarc/governance/cycles.json</code>, so the decision is reviewed instead of disappearing into a tool setting. See <a href="/docs/govern-cycle-exceptions">Govern cycle exceptions</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Can I export findings?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. Lenses can export raw files such as PNG, CSV, TSV, or DOT where appropriate, and AtlasArc can generate browsable Architecture Audit Reports with a Printable Version. See <a href="/product/features#review-and-report">Review and report</a>.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band" id="ci-governance">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">CI</span>
          <h2>CI and governance</h2>
        </div>
        <dl class="faq">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Does AtlasArc fail my build?</dt>
            <dd>The IntelliJ plugin does not fail builds by itself. Add the standalone evaluator as a pipeline step, or use the <a href="/docs/recipe-archunit-build">AtlasArc ArchUnit/JUnit rule</a> in a JVM architecture test. Both read the committed governance file and fail when an ungoverned problem cycle remains.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>How does the governance evaluator work?</dt>
            <dd>Your build first produces current JVM classes or TypeScript dependency artifacts. The standalone evaluator then reads those inputs plus <code>.atlasarc/governance/cycles.json</code>, using the same matcher and problem-graph classifier as the IDE. Remaining ungoverned cycle problems return a failing exit code. See the <a href="/docs/govern-cycle-exceptions#ci">CI setup</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Do I need AtlasArc in CI?</dt>
            <dd>You do not run IntelliJ in CI. Use the framework-free evaluator shipped with the matching AtlasArc release; it requires JDK 21 and explicitly configured compiler output or TypeScript artifacts.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Can my ArchUnit tests honour cycles accepted in AtlasArc?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. The AtlasArc ArchUnit adapter reads <code>.atlasarc/governance/cycles.json</code> and applies the same matcher and problem-cycle classifier as the IDE. A governed cycle passes; a new ungoverned cycle remains an ArchUnit violation. See the <a href="/docs/recipe-archunit-build">executable recipe</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Will the IDE and CI make the same governance decision?</dt>
            <dd>Yes for the same current evidence. They share schema version 1, evidence matching, debt precedence, reference-level red-wins behavior, and cycle classification. Invalid, stale, partial, ambiguous, or unsupported records fail closed in both surfaces.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="trial-licensing-support">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Buy</span>
          <h2>Trial, licensing, and support</h2>
        </div>
        <dl class="faq">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Is there a free trial?</dt>
            <dd>Yes. Every plan starts with a 30-day trial through JetBrains Marketplace. No card is required. See <a href="/pricing">pricing</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>What happens after the trial?</dt>
            <dd>Nothing is charged automatically. To keep using AtlasArc after 30 days, buy a plan through JetBrains Marketplace; otherwise the trial lapses. See <a href="/pricing">pricing</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>How is payment handled?</dt>
            <dd>JetBrains Marketplace handles payment, invoices, subscription management, and license keys. AtlasArc receives only the anonymised license metadata needed to validate your subscription. See <a href="/pricing">pricing</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>What is the difference between Personal, Commercial, and Team?</dt>
            <dd>Personal is for individual, non-company use: personal projects, open-source work, and learning. Commercial is a per-seat license for professional and company use. Team bundles seats into a 5-pack or 10-pack with centralised management for shared reviews and refactoring planning. All three include the full AtlasArc feature set. See <a href="/pricing">pricing</a>.</dd>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>Where do I get help?</dt>
            <dd>Use <a href="/support">support</a> for documentation links, bug reports, feature requests, direct contact, and JetBrains Marketplace support routing.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>
